  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A serving fork is used at the table for lifting roasted meat, presenting a fish fillet, or holding a joint while carving. The two tines must be even in thickness and length or the fork tips the piece it lifts. Birch carves cleanly "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "green",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "green-wood"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " and has fine, even grain that makes the narrow tine sections predictable to work. This is an intermediate project because the tine separation requires precise "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "stop cuts",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "stop-cut"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " to prevent the grain tearing into the tine base."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "infoPanel",
        "attrs": {
          "tone": "default",
          "title": "Before you start cutting"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "bulletList",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "listItem",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "Grip: four-finger grip on the work; thumb-push grip on the knife. Never make a cut whose blade-path can reach a body part."
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "listItem",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "Cut direction: push cuts and thumb-pivot cuts are the default. Pull cuts only with the work braced against the chest and the blade-arc unable to reach anything vital."
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "listItem",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "Sharpening: a dull tool slips. Strop every fifteen minutes of carving, hone weekly, oilstone monthly."
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "listItem",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "First aid: keep a styptic pencil, gauze, and a clean dressing within reach. A cut that shows fat or will not close with pressure goes to A&E, not a plaster."
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "listItem",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "Workspace: stable seat, good light, no children or pets within arm-and-blade reach."
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The wood"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Billet",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "billet"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ": 29 cm long, 5 cm wide, 3 cm deep. Birch from windfall or coppice. Cherry is a good substitute. The billet must have straight grain along its length; twisted grain makes matched tines impossible."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Tools"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "sloyd knife",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "sloyd-knife"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "; a carving axe for rough-shaping the handle (optional); a leather strop; raw linseed oil."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Method"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Mark the fork outline on the flat face: 18 cm of handle tapering from 2 cm wide to 1.5 cm wide; then 11 cm of tine section. Mark the tine split: a 7 mm gap between the two tines, centered on the long axis of the billet. Each tine is 11 mm wide. Draw the outline on both flat faces and on the side face."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "If using an axe, rough the "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "blank",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                        "attrs": {
                          "termSlug": "blank"
                        }
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " handle profile only. Work from the tine-shoulder toward the handle end. Never axe near the tine section."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Work the handle to its final oval cross-section with "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "thumb-pivot cuts",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                        "attrs": {
                          "termSlug": "thumb-pivot-cut"
                        }
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " at the shoulder and push cuts along the shaft. Then move to the tine section. First establish the outer edges of both tines with "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "push cuts",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                        "attrs": {
                          "termSlug": "push-cut"
                        }
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " running along each tine from shoulder to tip."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Cut the gap between the tines. Place a "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "stop cut",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                        "attrs": {
                          "termSlug": "stop-cut"
                        }
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " across the grain at the top of the gap (the tine shoulder line). Then make a push cut along the grain from the tip of the gap toward the stop cut, removing the waste in the gap. Work from both sides in alternating passes, deepening the gap 2 mm at a time until the full depth is reached."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Taper each tine from 8 mm square at the shoulder down to 4 mm square at the tip, then finish the tip to a rounded point with "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "slicing cuts",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                        "attrs": {
                          "termSlug": "slicing-cut"
                        }
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " at end-grain."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Check that both tines are the same length and the same diameter at each measurement point. A slight asymmetry is hard to see at the bench but obvious when using the fork."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Leave to dry on a shelf for 3 weeks before finishing. The tines are the thinnest part and most prone to checking."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Finishing"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Sand the handle through 120 and 180 grit along the grain. Sand each tine along its length to 180 grit. Apply raw linseed oil; cure 2 weeks before food contact."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Variations"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Three-tine version: add a third tine in the center. The gap calculation changes: two 5 mm gaps, three 9 mm tines."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Left-handed version: the fork is symmetrical; no adjustment needed."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Sycamore instead of birch: slightly coarser grain but more common as windfall."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Care"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Wash under warm water after use, towel-dry. Never dishwasher. Re-oil after every ten uses. Inspect the tine bases for cracks at each re-oil."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "heading": "What can go wrong",
          "intro": "Common problems and their fixes.",
          "items": [
            {
              "symptom": "Tine breaks at the base during carving",
              "cause": "Stop cut not deep enough before cutting the gap; grain tore past the stop line",
              "fix": "Cut the stop cut across the full width before any gap removal. The stop cut must be at least 5 mm deep before gap removal begins."
            },
            {
              "symptom": "Tines are unequal in length",
              "cause": "Tip shaping done freehand without measuring",
              "fix": "Mark the final tine length with a pencil line before tip-shaping. Work to the line."
            },
            {
              "symptom": "Tines check (split) during drying",
              "cause": "Drying too fast for the wall thickness of the tines",
              "fix": "Seal the end-grain of the tines with PVA glue before setting aside. Dry in a cool shaded place."
            }
          ]
        }
      }
    ]
  }
}